<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALBUM REVIEW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE HOCHMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Move Over, Perry Como, *** VARIOUS ARTISTS ,"The Unplugged Collection" Warner 
Bros.  
</P>
<P>
 There aren't any Christmas songs here, but this may be the best seasonal 
variety special since Perry Como's network heyday: 16 performances -- 11 never 
before on album -- collected from the trend-setting MTV acoustic music series, 
with a top-notch roster including R.E.M., Neil Young, Don Henley, Elton John, 
Paul Simon and Paul McCartney. 
</P>
<P>
 Remarkably, "Collection" (due in stores Tuesday) is not just a hodgepodge of 
tracks, but an expertly programmed set. 
</P>
<P>
 Opening with blues tunes by Stevie Ray Vaughan, Eric Clapton and Lenny 
Kravitz's surprising reworking of "Are You Gonna Go My Way" as a John Lee 
Hooker-like stomp, each rich performance leads nicely to the next,  
</P>
<P>
 Among the other previously only-on-TV highlights: Henley's emotional rendering 
of "Come Rain or Come Shine" and selections from Elvis Costello, k.d. lang and 
Soul Asylum . . . and not a clunker among them. New albums are rated on a scale 
of one star (poor), two stars (fair), three stars (good) and four stars 
(excellent).  
</P>
<P>
 STEVE HOCHMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
