<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: SAN FERNANDO; UNLICENSED DRIVER GETS 6 MONTHS JAIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE BERGER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Sylmar man was sentenced Friday to six months in jail for driving without a 
license after he told the court he was a "sovereign citizen" of the Republic of 
California and not subject to state or federal law. 
</P>
<P>
 David Sanders, 37, received the maximum penalty for the misdemeanor offense 
after representing himself in a one-hour trial in San Fernando Municipal Court 
earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
 He argued unsuccessfully that he subscribed to the Constitution of the former 
California Republic -- an antebellum document that gave "free white males" 
status as "common-law citizens" and enabled them to "drive conveyances" without 
regulation. 
</P>
<P>
 Unpersuaded, Judge L. Jeffrey Wiatt found Sanders guilty of driving without a 
license and driving an unregistered vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
 "He's definitely a high-level eccentric," said Deputy City Atty. Norman 
Wegener, who prosecuted the case. 
</P>
<P>
 Wegener said Sanders' case is not unique. He appears to belong to a loose-knit 
group of people -- many of them tax resisters -- who share a rejection of 
contemporary law and federal power. 
</P>
<P>
 Others have appeared in court for similar traffic offenses and, like Sanders, 
have received jail sentences in an effort to deter them from what Wegener 
called potentially dangerous beliefs. 
</P>
<P>
 "It doesn't take a great stretch of the imagination to think about what would 
happen if there was widespread driving of vehicles without any regulation or 
effort to ensure the drivers can see or even know what they are doing," Wegener 
said. "We'd have complete carnage on the highways." 
</P>
<P>
 Sanders was stopped in the Sylmar Square District on Aug. 25 after a Los 
Angeles police officer noticed he was driving without license plates. When the 
officer asked Sanders for his driver's license, Sanders replied that he did not 
have one and "didn't have to have one," Wegener said. 
</P>
<P>
 Sanders was being held at Los Angeles County Jail in lieu of $15,000 bail and 
could not be reached for comment. LESLIE BERGER 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
