<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOL FOOTBALL / CITY SECTION 4-A SEMIFINAL; SYLMAR'S PRICE IS RIGHT IN 
VICTORY OVER CARSON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK STRODER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Whether Carson High deserved to qualify for the City Section 4-A playoffs 
became a moot question Friday night before an overflow crowd at Sylmar High. 
</P>
<P>
 Carson, which entered the playoffs with a 2-8 record after forfeiting three of 
its games because of an ineligible player, was ousted after losing in the 
semifinals to fifth-ranked Sylmar, 27-19. 
</P>
<P>
 Durell Price rushed for 237 yards in 25 carries and scored four touchdowns to 
make sure Sylmar would advance to next Saturday's championship game against 
Crenshaw at El Camino College. 
</P>
<P>
 Regardless of the machinations that got the Colts into the playoffs, "I just 
couldn't see a (4-A) playoffs without Carson competing in them," Sylmar Coach 
Jeff Engilman said after the Spartans raised their record to 13-0. "They 
weren't a 4-8 ballclub. They have great talent on that team. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm just glad we got a chance to decide who the better team was on the 
field." 
</P>
<P>
 Price scored in every quarter, and three of the touchdowns were spectacular. 
</P>
<P>
 His 48-yard run down the right sideline with 7:18 to play gave Sylmar a 27-12 
lead. 
</P>
<P>
 "It means the world to me (beating Carson)," Price said. "All week long, I had 
been daydreaming about beating them and now the dream came true. It's an 
incredible feeling." 
</P>
<P>
 Carson had beaten the Spartans, 22-21, in last year's 4-A semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
 "We practiced all week long with the scoreboard showing, 22-21," Price said. 
"I couldn't get that score out of my head -- until now." 
</P>
<P>
 On Price's first score, a 51-yard run, he ran around right end and went 
untouched into the end zone, giving the Spartans a 7-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
 Midway through the second quarter, he fumbled on his own 22-yard line. The 
ball was scooped up by Carson's Eric David, who returned it 78 yards to cut the 
lead to 7-6. 
</P>
<P>
 Price answered with 1:52 remaining in the half when he scored on a 52-yard 
run. 
</P>
<P>
 He added a one-yard run in the third quarter, putting Sylmar up, 20-6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
