<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALEMANY TAKES ITS GAME TO ANOTHER LEVEL; GIRLS' BASKETBALL: INDIANS, LOOKING 
FOR WOODBRIDGE REMATCH, RISE TO DIVISION II-AA. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVE DESMOND, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Alemany High girls' basketball team will climb to Division II-AA, should 
the Indians qualify for the Southern Section playoffs, Coach Melissa Hearlihy 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Alemany, ranked second in the state, was placed in Division III-AA last month. 
The Southern Section classifications are based on enrollment, but schools have 
the option to move up one full division. 
</P>
<P>
 "If you have the caliber of team we have, you need to (move up)," Hearlihy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 The Indians have four returning starters from a 30-1 team that won the 
Southern Section Division II-A championship and advanced to the State 
semifinals last season. 
</P>
<P>
 Woodbridge, which defeated the Indians, 46-41, in that semifinal on its way to 
the Division II state championship, has been moved to II-AA based on 
enrollment. 
</P>
<P>
 It's not a coincidence that the teams are back together in the same playoff 
grouping, Hearlihy said. 
</P>
<P>
 "That game has been killing me," Hearlihy said of the semifinal, which Alemany 
led in the final minutes. "I've died a million deaths over that game since." 
</P>
<P>
 Alemany's request for the move was due by next Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 "And it will be approved," Southern Section Commissioner Dean Crowley said. 
"It's automatic." 
</P>
<P>
 Said Woodbridge Coach Eric Bangs: "On behalf of all the Division II teams, I 
can honestly say that this is definitely bad news." 
</P>
<P>
 By jumping to the higher division, the Indians have cleared a path for Newbury 
Park, which entered the season ranked 10th in the state, but would have played 
under Alemany's considerable shadow in Division III-AA. 
</P>
<P>
 Newbury Park Coach Nori Parvin received the news Friday morning in a phone 
call from Hearlihy, a close friend. 
</P>
<P>
 "She wanted to tell me in person," Parvin said. "She wanted another chance at 
Woodbridge and to give Newbury Park a shot. It's a long season, though, and 
anything could happen between now and the playoffs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Prep Sports 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA120394-0233 </DOCNO>
