<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS ALAMITOS; GOLDEN STATE FUTURITY FINDS ITS FIELD OF 10 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STACY PIGOTT, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ah Sigh and Meter Me Gone dominated Friday night's trials for the Dec. 16 
Golden State Futurity. Each easily won a trial division at Los Alamitos, with 
Ah Sigh posting the fastest qualifying time for the $200,000-estimated final. 
</P>
<P>
 Owned by Frank Nakamura and trained by Charlie Bloomquist, Ah Sigh took the 
lead early in the 400-yard race and, under jockey John Creager, won by 1 1/2 
lengths in 19.88 seconds for her seventh victory in eight starts. Alibis Assets 
ran second, a neck in front of Honey Who. 
</P>
<P>
 Far West Futurity winner Meter Me Gone was equally impressive, winning in 
19.99 seconds. With Kenny Hart in the irons for trainer Danny Cardoza, the 
colt, owned by Vessels Stallion Farm, crossed the wire 1 1/4 lengths in front 
of Mistoffelees. Casual Eyes was third. 
</P>
<P>
 The Connie Hall-trained Joes Tol won the third and last trial in 19.90 
seconds. Eddie Garcia rode the stakes-winning Tolltac filly, who is owned by 
Joseph Granone. A Dash Of Beduino finished second, with Doctor Mirth third. 
</P>
<P>
 The complete list of qualifiers for the Golden State Futurity: Ah Sigh, Joes 
Tol, A Dash Of Beduino, Meter Me Gone, Alibis Assets, Simply Scorching, Honey 
Who, Mistoffelees, Jungle Raised and Casual Eyes. Los Alamitos Notes 
</P>
<P>
 Patrons with a racing program from Thursday night's fog-shortened card can 
receive one free admission and program through the remainder of the Los 
Alamitos meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
