<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY ALMANAC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Knott's Berry Farm, which bills itself as "the oldest-living theme park," will 
mark its 75th anniversary in January. 
</P>
<P>
 The park was established in 1920 on land park officials describe as "the 
birthplace of the boysenberry." 
</P>
<P>
 Among its more popular attractions is the Calico Railroad, which is "held up" 
more than 10,000 times each year by actors.  
</P>
<P>
 Guests pan for real gold dust in the mine of Knott's Ghost Town. About $70,000 
worth of the dust is panned each year, park officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Knott's replica of Independence Hall is so accurate that Philadelphia's 
Bicentennial Reconstruction Committee asked for the park's plans when the 
original landmark's blueprints could not be found. Today 
</P>
<P>
 The Huntington Beach Fire Department will host a Holiday Disaster Expo from 10 
a.m. to 2 p.m. in City Council chambers, 2000 Main St. 
</P>
<P>
 More than 20 vendors will sell earthquake- readiness packs, first-aid kits, 
emergency food and water supplies, fire extinguishers, smoke detectors, tools 
and other items. 
</P>
<P>
 Free literature from nonprofit organizations on disaster preparedness will be 
available, and children can have their photo taken with "Surf City Santa." 
Information: (714) 536-5980. 
</P>
