812 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
1994-95 GIRLS' BASKETBALL / SMALL SCHOOLS; 1993-94 IN REVIEW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Academy 05,19,05,05,06,05 *2*League *2*Overall School W L W L St. Margaret's 8 
0 16 2 Liberty Christian 6 2 14 9 Cal Lutheran 3 5 9 7 Connelly 3 5 4 13 S.E. 
Lutheran 0 8 2 14 Highlights 
</P>
<P>
 For the second consecutive season, St. Margaret's went undefeated (8-0) in 
league play and reached the Division V-AA playoffs. And for the second season 
in a row, the Tartans lost in the first round, this time to Capistrano Valley 
Christian, 46-42. St. Margaret's only other defeat last season was to 
Capistrano Valley Christian, which moves to the Academy League in 1994-95. . . 
. Liberty Christian fell victim to Heritage Christian in the first round of the 
playoffs. . . . Susan Heydenrych was a first-team all-league selection for the 
second consecutive season. Kirsten Cappel and Georgina Cervantes of Connelly, 
Shay Trette of St. Margaret's and Lynlee Vaccaro of Liberty Christian also were 
selected. . . . St. Margaret's Brady Lock was coach of year. 
</P>
<P>
 Arrowhead 05,20,05,05,06,05 *2*League *2*Overall School W L W L Sherman Indian 
10 0 16 2 Hamilton 8 2 8 11 La Sierra Acad. 7 3 8 11 CSDR NA NA 7 11 La Verne 
Lutheran NA NA NA NA So. Cal. Christian 0 10 0 18 Highlights 
</P>
<P>
 The Arrowhead League sent four teams to the Division V-AA playoffs and each 
lost in the first round. Sherman Indian easily won the league title, but for 
the second consecutive season, lost to Arrowhead Christian, 66-43, in the 
playoffs. Anza Hamilton lost to the Olympic League's at-large team, Ontario 
Christian, 44-15. La Sierra Academy lost to San Bernardino Aquinas, 57-25, and 
CSDR was defeated, 56-29, by La Canada Flintridge Prep. Southern California 
Christian failed to make the playoffs, finishing last in the league without a 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
 Express 05,20,05,05,06,05 *2*League *2*Overall School W L W L Pioneer Baptist 
13 1 18 3 D. Calvary Chapel 11 3 11 9 Heritage Christian 10 4 14 8 L.B. 
Gethsemane 10 4 11 7 Rolling Hills Prep 4 10 4 11 Gateway Christian 4 10 4 14 
Bethel Baptist 4 10 4 15 H.B. Claremont 0 14 0 14 Highlights 
</P>
<P>
 Downey Calvary Chapel finished second in the league and lost in the first 
round of the Division V-AA playoffs to Avalon. . . . Heritage Christian was 
defeated by third-seeded Rio Hondo Prep in the second round, 60-38. Rio Hondo 
Prep advanced to the State regionals, where it lost in the first round. 
Heritage Christian defeated Liberty Christian, the Academy League's No. 2 
finisher, in the first round of the playoffs. Heritage Christian's Alisia Kean 
was a first-team all-league pick, averaging 15 points and 14 rebounds. Teammate 
Christa Larson received all-league honorable mention honors. 
</P>
<P>
 Olympic 05,20,05,05,06,05 *2*League *2*Overall School W L W L Cerritos Valley 
12 0 22 2 Calvary Chapel 8 4 16 9 Orange Lutheran 7 5 13 10 Whittier Christian 
7 5 14 11 Cap. Valley Chr. 5 7 13 12 Ontario Christian 3 9 10 12 Brethren 
Christian 0 12 3 19 Highlights 
</P>
<P>
 Five teams from the Olympic League went to the playoffs last season. 
Capistrano Valley Christian, which earned an at-large berth, made an impressive 
run, making it to the quarterfinals of the Southern Section Division V-AA 
playoffs, where it lost to Cambria Coast Union, 65-55. Andie Shaffner had 12 
points and 13 rebounds in the defeat. The Eagles defeated St. Margaret's, the 
Academy League's top team, 46-42, in a first-round matchup, and Avalon, 50-21 
in the second round. . . . Whittier Christian, which also received an at-large 
berth in the playoffs, made a surprising run. The Heralds were eventually 
defeated by second-seeded Sun Valley Village Christian, 60-49, in the 
quarterfinals. Village Christian made it to the State regional semifinals 
before losing. Alana Kempton, a first-team all-league selection, scored 16 
points in Whittier Christian's losing effort. The Heralds' ride began with a 
defeat of Alverno in the wild-card round, 40-27, and then an upset of Agoura 
Oak Park, the Tri-Valley League champion, 52-46, coming from 12 points down in 
the third quarter. Monique Moreno, also a first-team all-league selection, led 
her team with 15 points and went four for four at the free-throw line in the 
final 30 seconds to help secure the victory. . . . Orange Lutheran lost in the 
wild-card round, 71-62, to Cantwell Sacred Heart. Calvary Chapel, which also 
lost in the first round, fell to Riverside Notre Dame, 40-38. League champion 
Cerritos Valley Christian won its third consecutive Southern Section title and 
advanced to the State regional semifinals, where it lost to Santa Ynez, 65-60. 
. . . Blythe Linsey of Calvary Chapel, Shaffner from Capistrano Valley 
Christian, and Kristin Weddick and Lori Wright of Orange Lutheran were 
first-team all-league selections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
